i## Do I Recommend x32?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iRealistically speaking, I don't recommend using the x32 ABI for the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifollowing reasons:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Lack of software support		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Take Debian x32 as an example, a lot of programs (such as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     MariaDB) is not available in the repository, and you have to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     compile your own		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Once you met a strange problem or bug (although I haven't), don't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     expect any tech support available		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. No guaranteed performance improvement		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Like what I said, OpenSSL disabled assembly optimizations for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     x32, which slowed down encryption and decryption and canceled out		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     the benefits of x32		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - To save memory, you'd better directly use an x86 32-bit program		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     or Docker image		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut x32 is worth trying for tinkering purposes.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}